house\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01HRVa7fb8dLZr8gm58dVgwh\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"All passing. Here's a summary of the changes:\\n\\n**Two fixes in `e2e/agents/cursor_cli.go`:**\\n\\n1. **Premature WaitFor settle** (line 138): Changed the completion pattern from `a.PromptPattern()` (`/ commands`) to `Add a follow-up`. The `/ commands` text is always visible in Cursor's status bar — even during the \\\"Thinking\\\" phase — so when the model takes >2s to start producing output, WaitFor sees stable content and returns prematurely. `Add a follow-up` only appears in the input box after the agent finishes processing.\\n\\n2. **ENOENT config race** (lines 79-92, 182-213): Re-added `cursorConfigDir()` which creates an isolated `XDG_CONFIG_HOME` per tmux session with a pre-seeded `cli-config.json`. This prevents 43 parallel cursor processes from racing on the shared `~/.config/cursor/cli-config.json` via atomic temp-file rename. Cleanup is registered via `s.OnClose()`.\\n\\n`★ Insight ─────────────────────────────────────`\\n**WaitFor settle mechanics**: The tmux WaitFor implementation works by matching a regex, then waiting for content to be \\\"stable\\\" (unchanged) for 2 seconds. This is elegant for most agents where the prompt pattern only appears when truly idle. But Cursor's TUI is different — `/ commands` is always visible as a hint in the status bar. The fix uses a pattern that's *exclusively* a completion signal (`Add a follow-up`), not a persistent UI element. This is a common pitfall when testing TUI apps: status bar text that doubles as a \\\"ready\\\" indicator during startup can falsely signal \\\"done\\\" during processing.\\n\\n**Per-session config isolation pattern**: This mirrors how Claude Code E2E tests use `CLAUDE_CONFIG_DIR` — each parallel test gets its own config namespace. The key insight is that even pre-seeding a shared config file isn't enough when the